{"type":"message","id":"1ad6425c","parentId":"35a8337d","timestamp":"2026-04-13T05:01:14.329Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The QLHV cron (ed2d0b5d) has only ONE message in its history - seq 5 with `stopReason: aborted`. This is very odd. The cron started (it's in the sessions list as \"running\"), but it only has one empty assistant message that was aborted.\n\nThis means the cron is effectively stuck - it keeps getting aborted on each run. The gateway is probably:\n1. Starting the cron session\n2. The session tries to do something (maybe load context or send a message)\n3. The request gets aborted (timeout)\n4. The gateway re-starts the session\n5. Same thing happens again → infinite abort loop\n\n\n6. But here's the puzzle - the Lead IS receiving reports, which suggests either the cron is occasionally succeeding or the other cron running every 5 minutes is somehow handling the reports instead.\n\nLet me trace through the timing: the DTLX cron at 04:54 UTC delivered a report to the DTLX group, and the Agent Status cron also delivered to Lead at the same time. But the QLHV cron seems to be the one targeting the QLHV group, so I need to figure out which cron is actually generating the reports Lead is seeing.\n\nLooking at the session history, the QLHV cron has been stuck in an abort loop since 04:47 UTC - it's been trying to run every few seconds but keeps timing out, which means it's not actually sending any reports despite appearing active.\n\nThe real puzzle is that Lead IS receiving reports somehow. The 04:55 UTC report about the 4 active sessions is coming through, but I'm not seeing it in the QLHV cron session - it must be coming from a different source, likely one of the other cron sessions that's functioning properly. So I need to focus on restarting or fixing the QLHV cron that's stuck in this abort loop, since that's the one that should be delivering those reports to the QLHV group. The Agent Status cron is successfully delivering reports to Lead's Telegram every 10 minutes, which is why Lead sees the updates, even though the QLHV group cron is failing. The issue with the QLHV cron appears to be a context loading problem rather than a token issue, so I should restart it to see if that resolves the timeout loop.","thinkingSignature":"90088427196ab216bd7b8f2f3d07fd0b85fbeb0f86f87903813f8b5051c74353"},{"type":"text","text":"Cron QLHV (ed2d0b5d) đang bị **timeout loop** — chỉ có 1 message bị abort, gateway cố restart liên tục. Cần restart:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_1zr35xt5tup7_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"openclaw cron restart ed2d0b5d-fc56-42eb-a8fc-973a48024df7 2>&1 &\nsleep 8 && echo \"done\"","yieldMs":12000,"background":true}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"ahvholding","model":"AHV-Holding-DEV","usage":{"input":300,"output":604,"cacheRead":33480,"cacheWrite":696,"totalTokens":35080,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776056459147,"responseId":"062bab8ca6e449a8e1e508e767953ae9"}}
