{"type":"message","id":"367d5468","parentId":"0b603249","timestamp":"2026-04-13T05:02:23.760Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The `openclaw` CLI is completely hanging for all commands. This is the same issue we saw earlier. The gateway might be overloaded or the CLI is waiting for something.\n\nLet me try using curl to interact with the gateway API directly.Actually, wait. Looking at the MEMORY.md, the cron IDs are:\n- DTLX: `6f3323ef-607e-42a0-b946-611913081d31`\n- QLHV: `ed2d0b5d-fc56-42eb-a8fc-973a48024df7`\n\nAnd looking at the sessions list, the QLHV cron session `ed2d0b5d-fc56-42eb-a8fc-973a48024df7` has `status: running` but `stopReason: aborted` in its message history. \n\nThe cron is trapped in an abort loop because it's trying to send a message to the Telegram group and timing out, which triggers the gateway to restart it, creating an infinite cycle. Since I can't access the gateway API directly right now, I need to find another way to break this deadlock—maybe through the gateway's web portal or by identifying what's causing the send to fail in the first place.\n\nLooking at the actual report Lead is seeing, I realize the reports are coming from the \"Agent Status to Lead\" cron (e7885813), not the QLHV cron. That cron runs every 10 minutes and sends directly to Lead's Telegram, which explains why Lead is getting updates about the QLHV ecosystem even though the QLHV group cron itself is stuck. So the real problem is that the QLHV group cron is failing to send to the group, while the Agent Status cron is successfully delivering to Lead's direct chat.\n\nSince the openclaw CLI is completely unresponsive, I need to try accessing the gateway API directly or find another way to restart the QLHV cron and fix the underlying issue with the sessions_send call.\n\nLooking more carefully at the cron session history, I notice the QLHV cron only has one message with `stopReason: aborted` — but for the DTLX cron, I can actually see the full report content that was sent, whereas the QLHV cron is showing an empty message. This suggests the QLHV cron might be failing silently or the abort is happening before it can generate any content to send.\n\nThe `stopReason: \"Request was aborted.\"` in the DTLX cron is puzzling though — if the report was successfully delivered to the Telegram group, why would the request be marked as aborted? I'm wondering if there's a mismatch between what the cron session is reporting and what actually happened with the message delivery.\n\nLet me step back and focus on what I can actually verify: the DTLX cron is clearly working since Lead received the report in the DTLX group, the QLHV cron is stuck in a loop and needs to be restarted, and the Agent Status cron is also functioning and sending to Lead's Telegram. The real problem I need to solve is getting the QLHV cron out of this abort cycle so it can resume its 5-minute reporting cycle to the QLHV group. The issue might be with how the cron session is configured or how it's trying to send messages to the group. API directly.\n\nActually, let me think about this differently. The `openclaw` CLI is hanging because it's trying to connect to the gateway but the gateway isn't responding quickly enough. The gateway itself might be overloaded.\n\nLet me try a different approach: use the gateway's web UI or API directly via curl.\n\nWait, actually, let me reconsider. The MEMORY.md says the gateway is at `http://127.0.0.1:18789/`. Let me try to access it via curl.\n\nActually, I just realized something. The `openclaw` CLI commands are timing out, but the system is still functioning - agents are running, messages are being sent, crons are triggering. This suggests the gateway API is working fine for actual agent sessions, but the CLI is having trouble.\n\nThe CLI might be waiting for a TTY or some interactive input that isn't being provided. Let me try using `expect` or `yes` to pipe input to the command, or just use the `-