{"type":"message","id":"c6d4ec07","parentId":"5761edfd","timestamp":"2026-04-13T05:03:00.533Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I can see two `openclaw-gateway` processes running:\n- PID 1256: `openclaw-gateway` - CPU 37.5%, MEM 9.1% - VERY HIGH CPU!\n- PID 1281: `openclaw-gateway` - CPU 2.3%, MEM 4.3%\n\nThe first one (PID 1256) is using 37.5% CPU and 9.1% MEM - this is the main gateway process and it's working hard. This might explain why the CLI commands are timing out - the gateway is overloaded.\n\nActually, the high CPU on the gateway (37.5%) could be causing the CLI to be slow to respond. \n\nBut here's what's interesting - agents are still able to send messages through the gateway despite the high load, which suggests the API itself is functional. The CLI might just be getting queued behind other requests. I'm noticing there are two gateway processes running simultaneously, which is unusual - normally you'd only want one. The second one (PID 1281) could be a duplicate that's creating confusion. Let me look more closely at what's happening with those processes.\n\nThe first process is consuming 37.5% CPU and 9.1% memory, which is substantial for a long-running gateway, while the second is barely active. This high CPU usage could be what's causing the CLI commands to hang - the gateway might be so busy handling requests that it can't respond to CLI commands in a timely manner. Rather than restart the gateway and risk interrupting active sessions, I should probably just wait for the current operations to complete or try using the gateway API directly with curl instead of relying on the CLI.\n\nLet me think about this differently. I need to restart the QLHV cron that's stuck in a loop, but the openclaw CLI commands are all timing out because the gateway is overwhelmed. Using `nohup` to background the request probably won't help since it'll still wait for the gateway to respond. Let me try sending a task to the master-orchestrator session itself to restart the cron, though I'm realizing the timing doesn't quite add up - the QLHV cron was running at 04:47 UTC and it's now 04:56 UTC, so it's been running for about 9 minutes, which is longer than the typical cron interval.\n\nActually, the cron is probably catching the timeout and retrying, which is why it keeps showing as running. The simplest solution might be to just wait it out - the cron will eventually succeed or fail, and if it succeeds, it should auto-restart normally. Or I could try calling the gateway API directly using curl with an authorization token from the environment to bypass the CLI altogether. I could patch the database directly if I can locate it, but honestly, the real issue is that the QLHV cron is stuck in a loop trying to send to Telegram. Maybe I should just let it be—the \"Agent Status to Lead\" cron is already delivering reports to Lead every 10 minutes, so the QLHV cron failure is just a secondary concern. The question is whether the group -5168104492 is even still active or if that's why the cron keeps failing to deliver.\n\nNow I'm looking back at the session history for that group—it's marked as done with a runtime of 9205ms, and the last message from the assistant at 04:40 UTC was just responding to a heartbeat. So the session itself ended cleanly, but the cron is still trying to send to it, which is likely what's causing the loop.\n\nActually, I'm realizing the cron might not be failing at all. The `stopReason: aborted` could just mean the gateway timed out waiting for the cron to finish its work, not that the message send itself failed. If the cron triggered a `sessions_send` to the group and that call took longer than 120 seconds before the recent fix, the gateway would abort it—but the message might still have been queued or delivered in the background.\n\nLooking at the session timestamps, the cron started at 04:47:30 and the last activity was at 04:47:39, so it only ran for about 9 seconds before being aborted. That's suspiciously short for a full cron cycle that includes sending a message.\n\nThe gateway should've terminated it much sooner if it was a 5-minute cron, which makes me wonder if this cron is actually set to run every 10 seconds instead of every 5 minutes. But the actual QLHV cron that sends reports has a 300-second timeout, so the math still doesn't add up. The cron was probably stuck in an infinite retry loop because it couldn't reach the QLHV group session, and the gateway kept restarting it. I'm realizing the session key might be the culprit—when the group session ended, the cron lost the ability to send to it, triggering retries that got aborted. Rather than keep troubleshooting, I should just delete this broken cron and set up a new one with proper error handling, but since the CLI is hanging, I'll send a self-message to my session to restart it properly.\n\nNow I'm looking at the sessions_send call itself—it's trying to deliver a report to the group and then stop, but the API timeout of 120 seconds might be getting exceeded if there's a cold-start delay loading the session context. The cron is currently running (status: running) but it's trapped in an abort loop, stuck trying to deliver the same message over and over.\n\nThe real issue is that sessions_send is blocking for the full timeout duration before the gateway forcibly terminates it, which creates a vicious cycle. Since I can't directly interact with the CLI, I need to find a way to break this loop—either by having the master-orchestrator delete and recreate the cron, or by accessing the gateway database directly to reset its state.\n\nLet me check if there's an easy fix I can implement directly, like adding error handling to the cron or patching the session_send call.\n\nActually, I'm realizing the cron might just be waiting for the sessions_send to complete normally rather than timing out—the recent increase to 300 seconds means it's now giving the operation longer to finish. I should probably let it run with the extended timeout and see if it completes successfully this time. The cron is trapped in a retry loop because the group session has ended, so sessions_send keeps failing with a \"session not found\" error. To break this cycle, I need to either restore the group session, update the cron to target a different session, or fix the underlying issue with the session key itself. I'll have the master-orchestrator restart the cron with better error handling, possibly by switching it to use the direct session or the new group session instead.\n\nI'm realizing the QLHV cron runs every 5 minutes and sends to group -5168104492, while the Agent Status cron runs every 10 minutes and sends directly to Lead—so Lead is getting duplicate reports about the same QLHV work. The real priority is fixing the QLHV cron itself rather than worrying about redundancy. I'll try deleting the cron through the OpenClaw CLI with a timeout, though if that fails I might need to directly modify the gateway's cron state in the SQLite database.","thinkingSignature":"aac07f7bbae1f898aade20402fd5fe7eb1aef0aabc84f21c2b3cfb554defbaa6"},{"type":"text","text":"Gateway CPU cao (37.5%) đang làm CLI hang. Thử qua API trực tiếp:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_auuokwse4awy_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"find /root/.openclaw -name \"*.db\" -o -name \"*.sqlite\" 2>/dev/null | head -5","timeout":5}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"ahvholding","model":"AHV-Holding-DEV","usage":{"input":1189,"output":1551,"cacheRead":35638,"cacheWrite":1154,"totalTokens":39532,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776056544226,"responseId":"062babe1db09c518ddf8d0bbdb44d146"}}
