{"type":"message","id":"4c5b41a5","parentId":"8902fe31","timestamp":"2026-04-13T05:03:25.377Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good, simple commands work. The issue is that more complex commands (like `find`) were timing out. Let me now try to access the cron configuration from the tasks/runs.sqlite database. But actually, let me first understand what's in this database.Actually, the tasks/runs.sqlite might not contain the cron definitions - it might just contain the run history. Let me try to query it.\n\nBut wait, let me step back. The key issue is that the QLHV cron is stuck in a loop. The simplest fix might be to:\n\n1. Delete the QLHV cron and recreate it\n2. Or update its target session\n\nSince the CLI is hanging, let me try a different approach. Let me try using `openclaw` with a `--json` flag or other options that might make it non-interactive.\n\n\nActually, the CLI hanging is probably because it's a long-running process that's blocking on something. Let me try spawning a subagent to restart the cron instead - that's more reliable than trying to debug the CLI issue directly. Or I could try killing the stuck openclaw processes to see if that unblocks things. I noticed there are two openclaw-gateway processes running, which is unusual - normally you'd only have one, so having two might be causing resource contention and contributing to the hang.\n\nThe high CPU on PID 1256 (37.5%) makes sense for an active gateway handling multiple sessions, but it could also indicate a resource leak or memory pressure. Rather than trying to optimize the gateway directly, let me focus on fixing the QLHV cron itself. I think the cleanest approach would be to have the master-orchestrator send itself a message to run a one-shot task that deletes the broken cron and creates a new one, though that might be overkill. Instead, let me try something simpler - I'll use the sessions_send tool to send a message to the master-orchestrator's own ses