{"type":"message","id":"bc9ddcda","parentId":"cc584e74","timestamp":"2026-04-13T05:05:06.245Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"All the API endpoints are serving the web UI HTML, not JSON APIs. The gateway doesn't expose a REST API for cron management.\n\nOK, so I need a different approach. Let me think about how to fix the QLHV cron.\n\nThe QLHV cron is stuck because it can't find the target session. The simplest fix:1. Send a message to the group `-5168104492` to restart the session2. The cron will then be able to send to itOr:\n3. Spawn a subagent to recreate the cronOr:\n4. Wait for the gateway to restart (which would clear the stuck cron session)\n\nActually, the most pragmatic approach: Let me just send a message to the group `-5168104492` right now to restart its session. Then the cron can succeed on its next run.But wait - the group session ended at 04:40 UTC, and it's now 04:56 UTC. \n\nThe cron has probably racked up dozens of failed attempts by now, all stuck in the same loop. If the session was active, the cron would've succeeded immediately, so the issue isn't about timing or cold starts. Let me re-read the session history more carefully to see what actually happened. The session shows \"done\" at 04:40 UTC, but maybe it restarted since then and I'm missing something.\n\nActually, I just realized the cron runs every 5 minutes, not continuously. If it failed at 04:40, the next opportunity would've been 04:45, then 04:50, then 04:55. Looking at the timestamps, the cron started at 04:47:30 and only produced one message before being aborted—that's the 5-minute window kicking in. The cron ran, hit an error, got aborted, and the next run should've triggered at 04:50. But the session's last message was at 04:47 UTC, which means either the next runs failed silently or there's something else going on with how the session is being tracked.\n\nLet me check the session status directly at 04:55 to see what's actually happening with the cron runs. I think the real issue is that the cron session gets recreated each time it runs, so I need to find a way to delete the cron entirely rather than just aborting the current session. Since I can't use the CLI and the API routes don't seem to work for this, maybe I should try spawning a sub-agent to handle the cron deletion through a different approach.\n\nActually, I'm realizing the core problem might be simpler—the cron is trying to send a message to a Telegram group, but that group has rate limiting or is rejecting the message. Let me trace through what the cron is actually supposed to do: it's reading the heartbeat state, checking for changes, and then sending a report to the group, but maybe the send itself is failing silently or timing out. And there might be a separate issue with how the QLHV cron is configured that's preventing it from working properly.\n\nWait, looking back at the session data, I think I see what's happening—the QLHV cron at 04:47 UTC might have actually sent successfully, but then immediately got aborted by the gateway because its execution time exceeded the timeout threshold. The DTLX cron at 04:54 shows a similar pattern with an aborted status, so this could be a systemic issue with how long-running cron tasks are being handled.\n\nBut the content of those reports looks valid—there's actual report text there, not error messages. So maybe the `stopReason: aborted` is just indicating that the cron finished sending its report and then hit the timeout while trying to wrap up, not that the send operation itself failed. The gateway might be killing the process before it cleanly exits.\n\nLet me think about what's actually going wrong. The QLHV cron at 04:47 only shows one message and got aborted after 9 seconds, which is way too fast for a proper cron cycle. If it was doing a sessions_list call, that should've taken longer. My guess is the cron is failing during initialization—maybe when it tries to read the HEARTBEAT.md file or set up its initial state—and that's what's causing the premature abort.\n\nLooking at the session history, the QLHV cron only ran once and produced that single aborted message, which means subsequent runs either didn't create new sessions or didn't log anything. This could be a gateway-level issue where the scheduler is stuck in a retry loop, constantly trying to restart the cron but failing at the same point each time.\n\nActually, I think the cron did run multiple times—each run creates a NEW session, so old sessions show as \"done\" while the newest one is \"running.\" The current running session is just the latest attempt in that retry cycle.\n\nSo the real question is: why is the cron failing on each attempt? The most likely culprit is that it's trying to send a message to the Telegram group at -5168104492, which doesn't have an active session, causing the send to fail and the cron to abort.\n\nBut here's the thing—if the send is what's blocking and timing out, increasing the timeout to 300 seconds should fix it. Yet the cron still failed even after that change. So the issue isn't the send operation itself. Something else is causing the cron to fail during initialization or execution, and I need to look at what's actually in the cron session to figure out what's going wrong.\n\nWait, I'm realizing something. The cron session shows as \"running\" even though its last message was aborted, which means the session is still alive but stuck—it's waiting for something that never completes. The cron probably successfully sent its report in that first message, but then the session is stuck in a waiting state, which is why it keeps appearing as \"running\" even though it's not doing anything.\n\nSo the real issue is that the cron triggered, sent the report successfully, but then got stuck in a loop because the send operation didn't properly terminate. The cron keeps getting restarted and trying to send again, but it's caught in that same waiting state. If I look at the session details, the real problem is that the cron is stuck in a loop trying to send to a group session that either doesn't exist or isn't responding. The fix is straightforward: send a message to that group to recreate the session, which will let the cron break out of its retry cycle.\n\nAlternatively, I could delete the cron entirely and recreate it, but that requires CLI access which seems to be hanging. A third option would be to fix the cron script itself to handle this gracefully, though that also needs CLI. The simplest path forward is just sending a message to that group.\n\nWait, actually that might create a cascade—sending to the group creates a new session, the cron sends its report, then the session ends, and the cron gets stuck again in the next cycle. It's not a real fix.\n\nLet me step back and look at what's actually happening with the cron script, then think about whether I can delete and recreate it. The real issue seems to be in the cron itself, so I should focus on fixing the script rather than working around it.","thinkingSignature":"3edd3e13511ba09a8d2b301a62ec46bec2a854fd6f393be7357e81c81bf537b8"},{"type":"text","text":"Gateway đang serve web UI, không có REST API cho crons. Tìm cách khác:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_r2ni7qzfm4oq_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cat /root/.openclaw/tasks/runs.sqlite 2>/dev/null | head -c 4 | xxd | head -2; echo \"---\"; file /root/.openclaw/tasks/runs.sqlite","timeout":5}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"ahvholding","model":"AHV-Holding-DEV","usage":{"input":885,"output":1556,"cacheRead":42599,"cacheWrite":898,"totalTokens":45938,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776056667284,"responseId":"062bac5ca1418876e379fa4cb81e02eb"}}
