{"type":"message","id":"0c9ebb80","parentId":"5877b477","timestamp":"2026-04-13T05:05:38.195Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"`expect` is not available. Let me try using `python pexpect` or just use `yes` with pipe.Actually, let me try a different approach. Let me use `openclaw` with `--help` to see if there's a non-interactive mode.Actually, you know what? Let me just try the most pragmatic fix: send a message to the QLHV group to restart its session, so the cron can succeed. Then separately, work on fixing the HEARTBEAT.md to handle missing sessions gracefully.Wait, but if I send to the QLHV group, it will create a new session, the cron will succeed once, and then the session will end again, and the cron will fail again. \n\nIt's an infinite loop. I could enable change-detection mode in the HEARTBEAT.md so the cron only sends when there are actual changes, but that won't help since it already fails before reaching the detection logic. Let me think about this differently—the QLHV cron is stuck trying to send to a session that's no longer active. What if I make it detect that condition and gracefully exit instead of retrying indefinitely?\n\nActually, the real issue might be upstream. Let me check the cron trigger itself—maybe it's configured to restart too aggressively, or there's something in the scheduler causing the timeout. Looking at the cron history, the last run started at 04:47:30 UTC and shows only one message before timing out, which suggests the scheduler might be retrying too quickly.\n\nLet me try a simpler approach: just send a test message to the QLHV group to see if that kicks off a new session and gets things flowing again.","thinkingSignature":"bf1c04a36eee9fd9e6b6201b25fd89bad9a07ad112c294794a252781e0744d21"},{"type":"text","text":"Để tôi thử gửi message tới group QLHV để khởi tạo lại session, giúp cron thoát khỏi loop:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_926ebaxq32ab_1","name":"sessions_send","arguments":{"sessionKey":"agent:master-orchestrator:telegram:group:-5168104492","message":"Orbis đang kiểm tra kết nối — cron đang thử khởi động lại.","timeoutSeconds":15}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"ahvholding","model":"AHV-Holding-DEV","usage":{"input":119,"output":471,"cacheRead":44280,"cacheWrite":2482,"totalTokens":47352,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776056727086,"responseId":"062bac98aa62e25eebda97d03d9ec2f0"}}
{"type":"message","id":"c2165109","parentId":"0c9ebb80","timestamp":"2026-04-13T05:05:56.627Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_926ebaxq32ab_1","toolName":"sessions_send","content":[{"type":"text","text":"{\n  \"runId\": \"01c01fe5-4725-4670-a614-f0163eaebc72\",\n  \"status\": \"timeout\",\n  \"sessionKey\": \"agent:master-orchestrator:telegram:group:-5168104492\"\n}"}],"details":{"runId":"01c01fe5-4725-4670-a614-f0163eaebc72","status":"timeout","sessionKey":"agent:master-orchestrator:telegram:group:-5168104492"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1776056756537}}
{"type":"message","id":"0b6b5225","parentId":"c2165109","timestamp":"2026-04-13T05:06:29.356Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The session send is timing out. This is the same issue - the group session at -5168104492 is ended, and the gateway is timing out trying to reconnect to it.\n\nSo the problem is clear: the group session at -5168104492 is ended, and ANY attempt to send to it (via sessions_send) times out. This is why the QLHV cron is stuck - it tries to send to the ended session, times out, gets aborted, and the gateway retries.\n\nThe root issue: **The group session at -5168104492 is unreachable.**\n\nWhy? The group might have revoked the bot's access, or the group might be otherwise inaccessible. But wait - the bot IS still in the group, right? Because the other crons are still sending to other groups successfully.\n \nThe distinction is becoming clearer: the DTLX group at -5168104492 shows as ended, while the QLHV ecosystem group at -5163901258 is still running and accessible. These are separate Telegram groups with different session states. The cron targeting the ended DTLX group keeps timing out because it can't reach that session anymore. I'm noticing a discrepancy in how these groups are labeled across different sources—the session display name says \"g-ahv-dtlx-ecosystem\" for -5168104492, but the cron is configured to target \"QLHV ecosystem.\" Meanwhile, the other session for -5163901258 is labeled \"g-ahv-qlhv-ecosystem\" and appears to be the active one. This suggests the cron might be pointing to the wrong group entirely, or there's confusion about which group is which. Let me trace through the original session setup to figure out which group is actually which. I'm realizing the cron jobs are routing to different groups than expected—the DTLX cron targets the DTLX group (-5168104492) which appears to be ended, while the Works cron goes to the AHV Works group (-5212380728), but the reports suggest they're both going to the QLHV ecosystem instead. Let me trace through the actual session data to figure out where these are really being delivered. I'm seeing that the QLHV ecosystem cron is targeting the wrong group entirely—it's set to send to -5168104492 when it should be sending to -5163901258 where the active session actually is. The Works cron is correctly pointed to -5212380728, so the real problem is that the QLHV cron has a misconfigured target group that's no longer active.\n\nBut wait, both cron jobs are showing as stuck with \"running\" status but last messages marked as \"aborted\"—that's suspicious. Let me look more closely at what the DTLX cron is actually doing, because it appears to have successfully delivered a report at 04:54 UTC despite the aborted status. The QLHV cron on the other hand only produced one message before being aborted, which suggests it failed much earlier.\n\nThe timing is interesting here: the QLHV cron started at 04:47:30 and got aborted within 9 seconds, while the DTLX cron started at 04:44 and delivered a report at 04:54—that's a 10-minute runtime, which aligns with a 5-minute cron that retried after an initial failure. Both are targeting the same group ID (-5168104492), so the question is whether they're actually both trying to reach the same Telegram group or if there's something else going on with how they're configured. I'm realizing there's a discrepancy in how these group IDs are being labeled—the session for -5168104492 is labeled \"g-ahv-dtlx-ecosystem\" but the MEMORY.md refers to it as the QLHV ecosystem, while -5163901258 is labeled \"g-ahv-qlhv-ecosystem\" in the session data. These might be two different groups entirely, and I need to figure out which one is actually which based on the session labels rather than the potentially outdated MEMORY.md documentation. Looking at the cron configurations, the DTLX cron is targeting the group at -5168104492, but there's a mismatch—the MEMORY.md labels this as the \"QLHV ecosystem\" when it should be the DTLX ecosystem based on the session names. The active development work is happening in the group at -5163901258, which appears to be where the real-time development session with the backend and frontend agents is running.\n\nThe issue is becoming clearer: the cron at -5168104492 might be sending reports, but the active development at -5163901258 is where the actual work happens, so the reports might not be reflecting what's currently in progress. I need to verify whether -5163901258 is actually the DTLX group by checking the context file and understanding which group is truly the DTLX ecosystem versus which one is the QLHV ecosystem, since the session labels seem to be swapping the names. I'm realizing I've been confusing the group IDs and their actual purposes. Let me reconsider: group -5168104492 is actually the DTLX ecosystem where active development happens with those backend and frontend agents, while group -5163901258 is the QLHV ecosystem where older subagent failures occurred. The cron job ed2d0b5d sending to -5168104492 is correct for the DTLX ecosystem, but that group's session ended around 04:40 UTC, which is why the cron is failing to deliver there. So there's a mismatch between what the cron thinks it should be doing and what's actually happening in the active session. So the QLHV group cron is actually targeting the wrong session entirely—it's trying to send to the DTLX ecosystem instead of the QLHV ecosystem where the active development work is happening. The real problem isn't just that the group session ended, it's that this cron was pointing to the wrong group from the start.\n\nNow I'm seeing the solution clearly: I need to update the QLHV cron to target the correct group (-5163901258), delete it and recreate it with the right settings, or redirect its output to Lead's direct chat instead. The tricky part is that the group session at -5163901258 is currently active with the master orchestrator already running in it, so adding another session might create conflicts or duplicate messages.\n\nThe cleaner approach is to fix the cron directly using the gateway's WebSocket CLI instead of relying on the HTTP API. Let me try accessing the OpenClaw configuration file to update the cron settings there, since that's where the scheduler should store its configuration.","thinkingSignature":"27a65d15cef801ee660b132cb8d5424669536b4fc218a3f5e5cf5a4f70247794"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_pcb388yqnwts_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"ls /root/.openclaw/ && echo \"---\" && ls /root/.openclaw/gateway/ 2>/dev/null | head -10","timeout":5}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"ahvholding","model":"AHV-Holding-DEV","usage":{"input":169,"output":1419,"cacheRead":45935,"cacheWrite":1320,"totalTokens":48843,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776056756633,"responseId":"062bacb67c1c93cfd34b3c27d0ff3869"}}
